 Hydrogen Worst-Case Scenario
 The worst-case scenario is the EPA-mandated assumption that the entire contents of the largest containers in the plant storing the hydrogen - 8,884 pounds - will be released to the atmosphere in 10 minutes. This scenario would correspond to the catastrophic failure of the hydrogen tank.  This scenario is the WCS as defined in the CalARP regulation sections 2750.3 (a)(2)(A) and (c)(1).  The release results assumed the following conditions for a WCS:

?Neutrally buoyant gas;
?Ten-minute release at the rate of 888.4 pounds per minute (actually flash vaporized almost instantaneously);
?Urban topography;
?F stability class; and,
?Wind speed of 1.5 meters per second.

Results of the worst-case analysis are presented below.

?Using RMP comp with the worst-case meteorological conditions, the end point distance for hydrogen is estimated at about 0.2 miles from the facility shown on Figure 3.
?Using 2000 census data from Land View V, no residences, schools or hospitals are located within the worst-case distance (Figure 3).

Hydrogen Alternative Release Scenario
